More Info 👇

1. Don’t always focus on the subject. 
Our initial reaction when taking a photo is focus on the person or the closet thing. Changing this focus can add interest to the photo and can surprise the viewer in a good way. Use low aperture settings to make this focus change more noticeable!

2. Change your perspective. 
Don’t let yourself stay at the same level looking straight forward. Move your feet, lay on the ground, challenge yourself to look up, etc. You will be surprised what you might capture 😊 

3. Capture movement. 
One of the best ways to get a natural looking photo is to capture movement. Use what you have around you such as a gust of wind or instruct your subject to move. The sharpest photos don’t always look best. You can play around with different shutter speeds and allow blurring when you want. 

Hope this helps! 
.
#photographytips #learnphotography #bts #photography101 #photographer

6 places I was skeptical about going to, that were absolutely worth it! 
.
1. Rainbow Mountain - we had to convince our driver to take us at 2 am and hike in freezing high altitude conditions. We risked missing our flight to make this happen.
.
2. Allerton Gardens - This stunning place in Kauai is one of the few places in the world where you can see a Morton Bay Fig. 
.
3. Salt Flats - I lived my entire life close to these salt flats and never decided to go to them until I was 25 years old. Not sure what took me so long 😅
.
4. Golden Gate Bridge - I thought it would be overrated but it’s my favorite place to photograph to this day ❤️
.
5. Lake Powell - this had to make the list, I grew up going here every summer. When I went back it was better than I remembered!
.
6. Niagara Winter - I was convinced to go to Niagara Falls in well below freezing temperatures. I was extremely skeptical of going but ended up capturing some of my favorite pictures of all time.
.

More details 👇
These concepts probably aren’t new to you but when do you use them and why? 

1. Create Scale - this can be done in so many ways, but the idea is to use an object that the size is generally recognizable for someone looking at the picture such as a car, a person, a canoe, etc. This can be used when you want to show how huge the mountain is, how vast the lake is, or how deep that canyon goes.

2. Leading Lines - this is a popular composition topic where you guide they eyes of the viewer to a point of interest. If photos are not composed well, they can look messy and the viewer might not know where to look. Use leading lines to take the viewers focus on a little journey to your focal point:)

3. Simplify - there are so many situations where less is more. If you’re feeling overwhelmed with too many elements or you can’t find that right composition, can you cut things out? For example, can you put on a zoom lens and focus on a small portion of the scene? Look for something that can stand alone.

Here are 3 things to think about that will help when working with Natural Light in @lightroom!

- Compose with the light source in mind 
- Don’t fight the conditions, capitalize on them! 
- Exaggerate the light source 

Composing: it was snowy and cloudy which made for very flat moody lightning. I composed a photo using the little light I had to my advantage by creating a sort of zigzag with: 
- The rocks in the foreground 
- The tall rocks in the back
- And the small amount of light coming through the clouds. 

Don’t fight the conditions: In Lightroom, I always start with balancing exposure and adjusting the colors. 
- I want to exaggerate the moody lighting by adding blues into the highlights and shadows but leaving the midtones so the red rock could keep its color.

Exaggerate light source: When masking this picture, I use a manual process for Dodging and Burning which works really well for more flat photos. Manual as it is, this method will give you tons of control. 
- I always use a brush to exaggerate the light areas and another to darken the shadows.
- Tip: Always use the existing light as your guide, don’t go overboard and lighten areas that light couldn’t naturally be hitting. I use the Shadow brush to bring attention away from areas of the picture that are less important. Making sure your brush is feathered will soften the photo. I often use a very feathered Radial filler to enhance and give some color to my light source.
#MadeWithLightroom #adobepartner

More info 👇

Focal point - You need to find something that stands out from its surroundings.

Rule of thirds - you don’t have to put your focal point on an intersecting line but it’s a great place to start. Regardless, you can still use it to make sure I’m spacing things out well in your photos. 

Visual Weight - This is anything that draws the attention of the viewer. Even empty space is a notable area of the photo so use it while you’re balancing. 

Balance - I find that symmetrical tends to be really effective when it’s unexpected, something that doesn’t always look so balanced. Asymmetrical is still finding balance but using different elements/objects to achieve it. 

Triangles - If your asymmetrical photos don’t look balanced, triangles are an easy way to place objects around the frame. Use rule of thirds to help you space things out. 

Dynamic Tension - this concept can get very complex but it’s making clear separations in your picture. It will make the photo more interesting if you are changing patterns, textures, or focal points throughout. 

Horizons - this is an easy example where you can make separations between elements. Intersecting lines can be incorporated to increase the dynamic tension. (like buildings or roads) 

Depth - Foreground, middleground, background...You can increase the depth perception by changing your depth of field on your camera or incorporating leading lines. 

Leading lines - Support your focal point! Most common ways leading lines are - roads, trails, or rivers. Look for unexpected lines such as shadows or light.

Framing - Don’t overwhelm your focus! Find elements to frame the focal point while still adding interest to the photo. Don’t forget that negative space.

Scale - Humans, cars, or houses are examples of things that are consistent (ish) in size. When adding these things to a scene, it can show how vast the landscape is or how tall that mountain is. 

#composition #learnphotography #photogram #photography101

Things you need to do as a traveling photographer | Part One: Shooting in RAW

Let’s talk about why you should shoot in RAW! You may have been told this before but has anyone explained why? In both color detail and light, you will retain so much more detail in a RAW file, giving you more control while editing. I wish I had a dollar for every time I’ve heard, “OH NO, I’ve had my camera set to Jpeg.” Getting in the habit of taking and editing RAW photos will give you no regrets when you get home from a trip. 

Mobile tip:  if you primarily shoot with your phone, @lightroom for Mobile has options where you can capture RAW photos right on your phone.

There are definitely use cases when you don’t need a RAW file, but remember that RAW files can be exported as Jpegs. Jpegs can’t become RAW files…. Once a Jpeg, always a Jpeg…. 

Now that you are used to capturing beautiful RAW photo files, join me in part 2 where we’ll talk about getting your presets onto your mobile device. This will make editing while you travel so much easier! #learnphotography #travelphotography #photography #paigetingey

More details👇
1. Framing 
Framing is talked about so much yet commonly incorrectly incorporated. Framing should not overpower your focal point, it should help draw focus to it! Find an element or elements to position around your frame and remember that balancing with negative space can be very powerful.

2. Unique Light
The times for the “best light” will change based on your location and weather conditions. These seemingly less ideal shooting conditions might be an opportunity to find unique light. Move around and get creative with what you have. Foggy conditions can create beautiful light rays or even dirt can help you exaggerate the light (as seen in photo two). 

3. Use Reflections 
Reflections can make a complex scene more visually appealing while also making simple scenes more interesting! In both types of scenarios, it’s an effective way to give balance to the elements you’re working with. 

Thanks for watching! 
.

Things you need to do as a traveling photographer | Part Two: Mobile Editing & Saving Presets

Before your trip, make sure you save your presets! Editing can be time consuming and oftentimes you will have generally consistent settings from photo to photo. As time goes on, you’ll start to build up your own little portfolio of presets for various lighting situations. This will make your life soooo much easier once you’re on the go. 

Now make sure your presets are on your mobile device!  If you create or save your presets in Lightroom for Desktop and you log into your account on your mobile device, this will automatically sync your presets. The second way is exporting a photo that has the preset on it as a DNG, sending that to your mobile device, and uploading it so you can create a preset with those edits.

You are now prepared to travel like crazy! In Part 3 we will talk about easy adjustments you can make to ensure your presets look good on all your photos. #photographer #travelphotography #presets #learnphotography

Creating your own cohesive editing style | Part 2 - If you want to isolate and match your colors, you should first understand what components make up a color: 

• Hue - Changes the root of the color 
• Saturation - Changes the tone or how much gray is in  your Hue (color)
• Luminance - Changes the brightness of the color

A lot of editing styles will have consistency in the way they use these sliders. You can make individual colors pop, while muting other colors. 

*Tip - The color sliders you use to target a color may change depending on the light - this is common for greens! For example, if you have greens that are in the shade, you’ll often use your GREEN color sliders to adjust it, but when sunlight is hitting those same greens, you may need to use the YELLOW color sliders to make adjustments.

Stay tuned for part 3 when we talk about Color Grading! #MadewithLightroom #AdobePartner #photoediting

Since we normally see the world from an eye level perspective, we get used to this view. When we change our perspective as the photographer, we can show something unexpected. This fresh take will catch people’s attention. Drones are becoming more and more popular for this same reason. 

Next time you’re feeling uninspired while photographing, try photographing from below or above. One of my favorite change ups is to widen my focal length, get closer to my subject, and drop the camera close to the ground. The possibilities are endless so get creative!

What did I do to become a better photographer in 2023⬇️ 

First - my goal was to take time to learn more about the technical world of photography such as light, color, composition, and how my camera works. I wanted to learn more about the “why I do” behind the “what I do”. This has brought back so much love for photography for me, it’s been good to challenge myself!

Second- was to travel more to NEW places. This isn’t necessary but for me, I enjoy doing photography so much more when combined with seeing a new place. It’s what got me to love photography in the first place so I wanted to challenge myself to go to places I’d never been! 

Third - care less what other people think of my photography! If you want to edit something to look like film, do it, if you want to use photoshop, do it, if you want to saturate the hell out of something, do it. At the end of the day, it’s MY art. 

Thanks to all of you who support me and love my art! It’s so motivating for me to keep sharing the things I love ❤️

More details 👇

This is one of the hardest photos I’ve take for 2 main reasons! 

First - This photo was taken in the middle of the day which means the sky is super light and there’s sun outside the canyon. This canyon is tight so hardly any light gets in. No matter what camera you’re using you won’t be able to properly expose this entire picture in one photograph. This means you have to bracket which is taking multiple photos at different exposures so you can combine them later. 

Second - to keep everything sharp in the photo you have to focus stack. This again means taking multiple photos focusing on different areas on the canyon walls to combine in post processing. So, not only are you combining different exposures but also different focus areas in the final photo. 

And before you ask, NO the moon was not part of the original photo, I combined a total of 6 photos together to create this final image. This was such a fun challenge to teach myself some different skills that I hadn’t used before. Would I do it again 😅 maybe? 

#photography #learnphotography #editing

Adding Scale ⬇️

I use this concept possibly more than any other compositional element because it can be combined with pretty much any other element! This is a great way to have someone walking up to your photo / video saying “wow”. Especially when combined with depth, this makes you feel like you are standing in the picture rather than looking at it. Some tips on how to start⬇️

Use familiar objects:
The goal is that someone looks at the picture and knows how big an object is in real life, this enables them to use this as a reference point naturally sizing up the rest of the elements in the photo. For example, you can’t really tell how vast a mountain might be until you put a person, car, tree, house, or really anything that has a generally consistent size, in front of it. 

Play with perspective:
Sometimes getting yourself off “regular” eye level perspective will completely change the scale. For example, shooting from a low angle can make your subject appear larger and more imposing, while shooting from a high angle can make it appear smaller and more vulnerable.

Emphasize distance:
This might sound like depth because it basically is…. Breaking up elements in the foreground, middle ground, and background can help convey the scale of your subject. By emphasizing the distance, you can create a sense of scale that highlights your subject’s size relative to its surroundings.

Incorporate human elements:
Including people in your compositions is one of most effective objects to add. The viewer can easily relate to the size of a person, making it easier to understand the scale of other elements based on the person.

Experiment with lens choice:
Wide-angle lenses can exaggerate the size of objects in the foreground while making those in the background appear smaller while telephoto lenses can compress the distance between objects. This compression is a great way to bring the background closer in creating a more uniform sense of scale.
